metadata.description:
Sillage
[si: 'ja:z] noun ‚Ä¢ French

A scent that lingers in the air; the impression made in space after something or someone has been and gone; the trace of someone's perfume.

Step into the world of Sillage, where art meets code to craft unique narratives of fleeting existence, encapsulating the concept of presence and absence in a digital realm.

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #715
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash ‚Äî they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Texture pattern II #4
metadata.description:
Texture #pattern II is a counter-intuitive visual experiment, it is about creating difference through repetition. One parameter changes in the repetition of fixed sequence in a grid within a grid, this bit of interference creates new patterns by repetition with different visual results.

The piece allows simple interaction, you can click/touch and the colours change within the logic of the algorithm, while maintaining the uniqueness of each token, almost endless variations within each piece are posible. 

You can also add or subtract additional lines or noise to alter its texture.

‚Ä®'s' saves a png‚Ä®
'j' saves a jpg‚Ä®
'1','2','4' sets the pixel density to 1,2,4‚Ä®
'l' allows you to toggle the texture made by lines 
'+' adds more lines
'-' removes lines
'n' allows you to toggle extra noise‚Ä®'m' adds more noise‚Ä®'b' removes some noise‚Ä®

metadata.name: Glyphs #42
metadata.description:
Glyphs attempts to expand upon the seemingly random, yet beautiful forms found in the world around us. They capture the structured randomness in everyday life. 

Inspired by the handwritten form and the spatial complexities of figure ground maps within the urban context.

Glyphs are randomly produced within a set of rules, some more complex than others.

There are 11 color palette options, each containing a number of specific color options.  

Two main graphics options require different compute times. Faded outputs will take longer to render than others. For this reason I have required a 60s view capture to ensure everyone gets a thumbnail regardless of the features.

‚ÄúS‚Äù - save image as .JPG

Glyphs | cmplx 2022 | JPG | 2500x2500

metadata.name: PEGS #451
metadata.description: Taking inspiration from work by Karl Gerstner, Armin Hofmann, Nick Kuder and Dmitri Cherniak, PEGS explores the limits of constrained algorithmic variation. Based on the simple, playful idea of wrapping a string across a board of pegs, it shows how endless possibilities can be achieved with just a basic set of rules and a few primary colors. When done right, generative art challenges us to answer fundamental questions around creativity, beauty, and life itself.

metadata.name: Dynamic generations #190
metadata.description:
A classic cellular automata updates its state with a static rule based on the state of its neighbor.

This collection was created with cellular automata with an extension of that idea. Here the state and the rule are updated based on the state of its neighbor, here the rule changes in every iteration, here the rule is dynamic.

That change moves cellular automata to another level of complexity.

metadata.name: trƒÅma #89
metadata.description:
trƒÅma is part of the interactive minting experience at NFT Show Europe, Valencia, 2023.

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

trƒÅma is a project in continuity with a wider body of work exploring the subject of computers as a source of aesthetic phenomena.

Beyond being utilitarian machines, is it possible to have such devices not only as mediators between representational content and humans, but also as aesthetic manifestations that connect to our senses?

The low visual resolution, the motion, and the timing of the work are informed by early computer graphics, mechanical displays and the rawness that older computational systems tend to carry.

trƒÅma features a generative system, conducted through realtime custom software that runs in the browser.


++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

metadata.name: Redundancy #13
metadata.description:
This generative token explores redundancy as an architectural concept, method, and process. Redundancy provides flexibility in an open form, enabling a shift from monofunctional to multifunctional as well as from optimized to resilient. A hybrid architecture in which complexity is created through the continuous reconfiguration of simple discrete and compatible blocks.
Each minted redundancy token reveals various deterministic rare features, styles, and scales, creating endlessly redundant open architectures. 

Redundancy Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #885
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Charcoal Brutalism #146
metadata.description:
Based on a similar technique as "Charcoal Landscapes", using lines limited to 8 possible directions, this work is about the repetition of patterns at different scales and the use of negative spaces.
The texture created from the noise combined with the structures that emerges from this algorithm create a look similar to the brutalist architecture of the last century.

There are 10 scale variations but with almost infinite possible outcomes.
Inverted colours have a small chance of dropping.

Original artwork by William Watkins ¬∑ Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: BETWEEN #23
metadata.description:
Between thought and embodiment.
A color that is not perceived by the human eye - is a radio wave.
